    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-05-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-05-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="481"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d481">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003 C 73/41</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chinese Minister</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sze</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-05-11">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 11, 1923</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your Legation’s note of May 4, 1923, advising me of the readiness of your
                    Government to have the Commission on Extraterritoriality in China, provided for
                    in the Resolution adopted on December 10, 1921, by the Washington Conference on
                    the Limitation of Armament, meet at Peking on November 1, 1923.</p>
                <p>In reply I have the honor to inform you that the meeting of the Commission at
                    Peking at the time stated will be very agreeable to this Government, and that I
                    have, by way of compliance with the request made in the note, instructed the
                    appropriate American diplomatic officers to communicate copies of the note to
                    all the Governments concerned.<note n="60" xml:id="d481fn60">Copies of the note
                        were mailed to the appropriate American diplomatic representatives on May
                        11, and, on the same date, a circular telegram was sent instructing that the
                        Foreign Offices be informed that the Chinese Government had indicated that
                        it would be agreeable to have the Commission on Extraterritoriality meet at
                        Peking Nov. 1, 1923.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles E. Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
